	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Edgar Mitchell, an Apollo 14 astronaut and moonwalker, presented University of Central Florida senior Benjamin Corbin with a $10,000 scholarship from the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation during a public presentation and ceremony on Thursday, Nov. 15</p>
<p>The award is one of 19 made available each year through the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation. The scholarships are awarded to college students who exhibit exceptional performance, initiative and creativity in the science or engineering field of their major. While scholarship recipients must display intellectual daring, the committee also looks for well-rounded students who are involved in campus and community activities.<br />
&nbsp; <br />
&ldquo;These scholarships are a way for me and my fellow astronauts to give back to a country that provided us with an extraordinary opportunity,&rdquo; Mitchell said. &ldquo;Benjamin will be one of the many leaders who will keep the United States at the edge of breakthrough technology, and I consider it an honor to be presenting him with this check.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The award will be applied toward Corbin&rsquo;s continuing education at UCF, where he holds an overall grade point average of 3.9 and is studying Aerospace Engineering. With his interest in space exploration and science, he has conducted research in the field of gas dynamics and plans to do research in aerospace engineering and astrophysics.</p>
<p>Eventually, he would like to work with ion engines and long-range impulse thrusters on rockets, or become an astronaut himself. Corbin, of Fort Walton Beach, has received his pilot&rsquo;s license and is continuing his aviation education to earn his instrument flight rating.</p>
<p>At NASA&rsquo;s Ames Research Center, he participated in a simulated Mars mission, where he served as chief engineer. He joined the Society of Physics Students and volunteers as a tutor.</p>
<p>Corbin currently serves as president of Students for the Exploration and Development of Space and is actively involved with UCF&rsquo;s engineering honor societies. In addition to the valuable research he is performing at UCF with Eric Petersen, Corbin recently attended the International Space University Summer Session Program in Beijing, China.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ben is an outstanding student who is committed to advancing scientific discoveries in space,&rdquo; said UCF President John Hitt. &ldquo;He is a fine example of the many talented and dedicated students at UCF, and it is clear to anyone who meets him that Ben will make a significant contribution to the U.S. space program.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Corbin is the second UCF student to receive an Astronaut Scholarship Foundation award during the past two years and the 16th overall. Brian Becker, then a senior Computer Engineering major, won a scholarship in 2006.</p>
<p>Mitchell was selected as a NASA astronaut in April 1966 after graduating first in his class from the Air Force Aerospace Research Pilot School, where he was both a student and an instructor. He was assigned to Apollo 14 as Lunar Module pilot, and on Feb. 5, 1971, Alan Shepard and Mitchell landed their Lunar Module &quot;Antares&quot; in the Fra Mauro highlands on the moon, while crewmate Stuart Roosa orbited overhead in &quot;Kittyhawk.&quot;</p>
<p>During 33 hours on the moon surface, Shepard and Mitchell made two outside excursions during which they set up a nuclear-powered science station, collected 92 pounds of moon rocks and gathered deep-down soil samples by driving core tubes into the surface. Mitchell currently serves on the Board of Directors for the ASF.</p>
<p>The Astronaut Scholarship Foundation is a nonprofit organization established in 1984 by the six surviving members of America's original Mercury astronauts. Its goal is to aid the United States in retaining its world leadership in science and technology by providing scholarships for college students who exhibit motivation, imagination and exceptional performance in the science or engineering field of their major. ASF funds 19 $10,000 scholarships annually and has awarded nearly $2.5 million to 226 students nationwide. For more information, log on to <a href="http://www.AstronautScholarship.org">www.AstronautScholarship.org</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p>&nbsp;<strong>UCF Stands for Opportunity:</strong> Established in 1963, the University of Central Florida is a diverse metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th-largest in the country with more than 48,000 students. Located in Orlando, Fla., UCF offers high-quality undergraduate and graduate education, student development and continuing education, while conducting cutting-edge research that powers the region's economic development. For more UCF news, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
